tive self-exemption, Natsu Taylor Saito argues, undermines not only specific legal institutions and norms, but leads to a decreased effectiveness of the global rule of law. Meeting the Enemy is a pointed look at why the United States' frequent-if selective-disregard of international law and institutions is met with such high levels of approval, or at least complacency, by the American public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aExceptionalismxHistoryxUnited States. 0aExceptionalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aInternational lawxPublic opinion. 0aInternational law. 0aManifest Destiny. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 4aAmerican. 4aEnemy. 4aMeeting. 4aSince;founding;United;States;defined;itself;supreme;protector;freedom;throughout;world;pointing;Constitution;model;ensure;democracy;home;protect;human;rights;internationally;Although;consistently;emphasized;importance. 4aapproval. 4acomplacency. 4adisregard. 4adistanced. 4aestablished. 4afrequent. 4afrom. 4ahigh. 4aimplement. 4ainstitutions. 4ainternational. 4aleast. 4alegal. 4alevels. 4alook. 4amany. 4apointed. 4aprinciples. 4apublic. 4aselective. 4asimultaneously. 4asuch. 4asystem. 4athat. 4athem. 4awith. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814786512.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STME  aPDA5E